# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: classic-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] High-profile applications of AI include advanced web search engines, chatbots, virtual assistants, autonomous vehicles, and play and analysis in strategy games (e.g., chess and Go).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Since the 2020s, generative AI has become widely available to generate images, audio, and videos from text prompts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traditional goals of AI research include learning, reasoning, knowledge representation, planning, natural language processing, and perception, as well as support for robotics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] To reach these goals, AI researchers have used techniques including state space search and mathematical optimization, formal logic, artificial neural networks, and methods based on statistics, operations research, and economics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI also draws upon psychology, linguistics, philosophy, neuroscience, and other fields.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Some companies, such as OpenAI, Google DeepMind and Meta, aim to create artificial general intelligence (AGI) – AI that can complete virtually any cognitive task at least as well as a human.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Artificial intelligence was founded as an academic discipline in 1956, and the field went through multiple cycles of optimism throughout its history, followed by periods of disappointment and loss of funding, known as AI winters.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Funding and interest increased substantially after 2012, when graphics processing units began being used to accelerate neural networks, and deep learning outperformed previous AI techniques.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] This growth accelerated further after 2017 with the transformer architecture.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the 2020s, an AI boom has coincided with advances in generative AI, which allowed for the creation and modification of media.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In addition to AI safety and unintended consequences and harms from the use of AI, ethical concerns, AI's long-term effects, and potential existential risks have prompted discussions of AI regulation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The general problem of simulating (or creating) intelligence has been broken into subproblems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These consist of particular traits or capabilities that researchers expect an intelligent system to display.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traits described below have received the most attention and cover the scope of AI research.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early researchers developed algorithms that imitated step-by-step reasoning that humans use when they solve puzzles or make logical deductions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] By the late 1980s and 1990s, methods were developed for dealing with uncertain or incomplete information, employing concepts from probability and economics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many of these algorithms are insufficient for solving large reasoning problems because they experience a "combinatorial explosion": They become exponentially slower as the problems grow.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Even humans rarely use the step-by-step deduction that early AI research could model.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Humans solve most of their problems using fast, intuitive judgments.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Reasoning models, a type of large language model trained to generate intermediate chains-of-thought, emerged in 2024 and allowed improved performance on complex problems in mathematics and coding.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Knowledge representation and knowledge engineering allow AI programs to answer questions intelligently and make deductions about real-world facts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal knowledge representations are used in content-based indexing and retrieval, scene interpretation, clinical decision support, knowledge discovery (mining "interesting" and actionable inferences from large databases), and other areas.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A knowledge base is a body of knowledge represented in a form that can be used by a program.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] An ontology is the set of objects, relations, concepts, and properties used by a particular domain of knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is also the difficulty of knowledge acquisition, the problem of obtaining knowledge for AI applications.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] An "agent" is any entity (artificial or not) that perceives and takes actions in the world.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A rational agent has goals or preferences and takes actions to make them happen.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated planning, the agent has a specific goal.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated decision-making, the agent has preferences—there are some situations it would prefer to be in, and some situations it is trying to avoid.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision-making agent assigns a number to each situation (called its "utility") that measures how much the agent prefers it.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] For each possible action, it can calculate the "expected utility": the utility of all possible outcomes of the action, weighted by the probability that the outcome will occur.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can then choose the action with the maximum expected utility.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In classical planning, the agent knows exactly what the effect of any action will be.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In most real-world problems, however, the agent may not be certain about the situation it is in (it is "unknown" or "unobservable") and it may not know for certain what will happen after each possible action (it is not "deterministic").
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It must choose an action by making a probabilistic guess and then reassess the situation to see if the action worked.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Alongside thorough testing and improvement based on previous decisions, having an explanation for why the agent took certain decisions is a way to build trust, especially when the decisions have to be relied upon.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In some problems, the agent's preferences may be uncertain, especially if there are other agents or humans involved.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These preferences be learned (e.g., with inverse reinforcement learning), or the agent can seek information to improve them.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Information value theory can be used to weigh the value of exploratory or experimental actions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The space of possible future actions and situations is typically intractably large, so the agents must take actions and evaluate situations while being uncertain of what the outcome will be.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A Markov decision process has a transition model that describes the probability that a particular action will change the state in a particular way and a reward function that supplies the utility of each state and the cost of each action.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A policy associates a decision with each possible state.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The policy could be calculated (e.g., by iteration), be heuristic, or it can be learned.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game theory describes the rational behavior of multiple interacting agents and is used in AI programs that make decisions that involve other agents.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine learning is the study of programs that can improve their performance on a given task automatically.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It has been a part of AI from the beginning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are several kinds of machine learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Unsupervised learning analyzes a stream of data and finds patterns and makes predictions without any other guidance.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Supervised learning requires labeling the training data with the expected answers, and comes in two main varieties: classification (where the program must learn to predict what category the input belongs in) and regression (where the program must deduce a numeric function based on numeric input).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In reinforcement learning, the agent is rewarded for good responses and punished for bad ones.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The agent learns to choose responses that are classified as "good".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Transfer learning is when the knowledge gained from one problem is applied to a new problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning is a type of machine learning that runs inputs through biologically inspired artificial neural networks for all of these types of learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computational learning theory can assess learners by computational complexity, by sample complexity (how much data is required), or by other notions of optimization.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Natural language processing (NLP) allows programs to read, write and communicate in human languages.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specific problems include speech recognition, speech synthesis, machine translation, information extraction, information retrieval and question answering.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early work, based on Noam Chomsky's generative grammar and semantic networks, had difficulty with word-sense disambiguation unless restricted to small domains called "micro-worlds" (due to the common sense knowledge problem).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Margaret Masterman believed that it was meaning and not grammar that was the key to understanding languages, and that thesauri and not dictionaries should be the basis of computational language structure.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Modern deep learning techniques for NLP include word embedding (representing words, typically as vectors encoding their meaning), transformers (a deep learning architecture using an attention mechanism), and others.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, generative pre-trained transformer (or "GPT") language models began to generate coherent text, and by 2023, these models were able to get human-level scores on the bar exam, SAT test, GRE test, and many other real-world applications.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine perception is the ability to use input from sensors (such as cameras, microphones, wireless signals, active lidar, sonar, radar, and tactile sensors) to deduce aspects of the world.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computer vision is the ability to analyze visual input.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The field includes speech recognition, image classification, facial recognition, object recognition, object tracking, and robotic perception.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Affective computing is a field that comprises systems that recognize, interpret, process, or simulate human feeling, emotion, and mood.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, some virtual assistants are programmed to speak conversationally or even to banter humorously; it makes them appear more sensitive to the emotional dynamics of human interaction, or to otherwise facilitate human–computer interaction.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, this tends to give naïve users an unrealistic conception of the intelligence of existing computer agents.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moderate successes related to affective computing include textual sentiment analysis and, more recently, multimodal sentiment analysis, wherein AI classifies the effects displayed by a videotaped subject.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A machine with artificial general intelligence would be able to solve a wide variety of problems with breadth and versatility similar to human intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI research uses a wide variety of techniques to accomplish the goals above.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] State space search searches through a tree of possible states to try to find a goal state.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, planning algorithms search through trees of goals and subgoals, attempting to find a path to a target goal, a process called means-ends analysis.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Simple exhaustive searches are rarely sufficient for most real-world problems: the search space (the number of places to search) quickly grows to astronomical numbers.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The result is a search that is too slow or never completes.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] "Heuristics" or "rules of thumb" can help prioritize choices that are more likely to reach a goal.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Adversarial search is used for game-playing programs, such as chess or Go.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It searches through a tree of possible moves and countermoves, looking for a winning position.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Local search uses mathematical optimization to find a solution to a problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It begins with some form of guess and refines it incrementally.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Gradient descent is a type of local search that optimizes a set of numerical parameters by incrementally adjusting them to minimize a loss function.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Variants of gradient descent are commonly used to train neural networks, through the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Another type of local search is evolutionary computation, which aims to iteratively improve a set of candidate solutions by "mutating" and "recombining" them, selecting only the fittest to survive each generation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Distributed search processes can coordinate via swarm intelligence algorithms.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Two popular swarm algorithms used in search are particle swarm optimization (inspired by bird flocking) and ant colony optimization (inspired by ant trails).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal logic is used for reasoning and knowledge representation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deductive reasoning in logic is the process of proving a new statement (conclusion) from other statements that are given and assumed to be true (the premises).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Proofs can be structured as proof trees, in which nodes are labelled by sentences, and children nodes are connected to parent nodes by inference rules.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Given a problem and a set of premises, problem-solving reduces to searching for a proof tree whose root node is labelled by a solution of the problem and whose leaf nodes are labelled by premises or axioms.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the case of Horn clauses, problem-solving search can be performed by reasoning forwards from the premises or backwards from the problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the more general case of the clausal form of first-order logic, resolution is a single, axiom-free rule of inference, in which a problem is solved by proving a contradiction from premises that include the negation of the problem to be solved.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Inference in both Horn clause logic and first-order logic is undecidable, and therefore intractable.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, backward reasoning with Horn clauses, which underpins computation in the logic programming language Prolog, is Turing complete.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moreover, its efficiency is competitive with computation in other symbolic programming languages.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Fuzzy logic assigns a "degree of truth" between 0 and 1.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can therefore handle propositions that are vague and partially true.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Non-monotonic logics, including logic programming with negation as failure, are designed to handle default reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other specialized versions of logic have been developed to describe many complex domains.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many problems in AI (including reasoning, planning, learning, perception, and robotics) require the agent to operate with incomplete or uncertain information.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI researchers have devised a number of tools to solve these problems using methods from probability theory and economics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Precise mathematical tools have been developed that analyze how an agent can make choices and plan, using decision theory, decision analysis, and information value theory.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These tools include models such as Markov decision processes, dynamic decision networks, game theory and mechanism design.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Bayesian networks are a tool that can be used for reasoning (using the Bayesian inference algorithm), learning (using the expectation–maximization algorithm), planning (using decision networks) and perception (using dynamic Bayesian networks).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Probabilistic algorithms can also be used for filtering, prediction, smoothing, and finding explanations for streams of data, thus helping perception systems analyze processes that occur over time (e.g., hidden Markov models or Kalman filters).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The simplest AI applications can be divided into two types: classifiers (e.g., "if shiny then diamond"), on one hand, and controllers (e.g., "if diamond then pick up"), on the other hand.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Classifiers are functions that use pattern matching to determine the closest match.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] They can be fine-tuned based on chosen examples using supervised learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each pattern (also called an "observation") is labeled with a certain predefined class.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] All the observations combined with their class labels are known as a data set.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] When a new observation is received, that observation is classified based on previous experience.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are many kinds of classifiers in use.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision tree is the simplest and most widely used symbolic machine learning algorithm.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] K-nearest neighbor algorithm was the most widely used analogical AI until the mid-1990s, and Kernel methods such as the support vector machine (SVM) displaced k-nearest neighbor in the 1990s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The naive Bayes classifier is reportedly the "most widely used learner" at Google, due in part to its scalability.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks are also used as classifiers.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] An artificial neural network is based on a collection of nodes also known as artificial neurons, which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] It is trained to recognise patterns; once trained, it can recognise those patterns in fresh data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is an input, at least one hidden layer of nodes and an output.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each node applies a function and once the weight crosses its specified threshold, the data is transmitted to the next layer.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least 2 hidden layers.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Learning algorithms for neural networks use local search to choose the weights that will get the right output for each input during training.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The most common training technique is the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks learn to model complex relationships between inputs and outputs and find patterns in data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In theory, a neural network can learn any function.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In feedforward neural networks the signal passes in only one direction.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The term perceptron typically refers to a single-layer neural network.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In contrast, deep learning uses many layers.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNNs) feed the output signal back into the input, which allows short-term memories of previous input events.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Long short-term memory networks (LSTMs) are recurrent neural networks that better preserve longterm dependencies and are less sensitive to the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) use layers of kernels to more efficiently process local patterns.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] This local processing is especially important in image processing, where the early CNN layers typically identify simple local patterns such as edges and curves, with subsequent layers detecting more complex patterns like textures, and eventually whole objects.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning uses several layers of neurons between the network's inputs and outputs.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The multiple layers can progressively extract higher-level features from the raw input.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, in image processing, lower layers may identify edges, while higher layers may identify the concepts relevant to a human such as digits, letters, or faces.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning has profoundly improved the performance of programs in many important subfields of artificial intelligence, including computer vision, speech recognition, natural language processing, image classification, and others.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The reason that deep learning performs so well in so many applications is not known as of 2021.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPT) are large language models (LLMs) that generate text based on the semantic relationships between words in sentences.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Text-based GPT models are pre-trained on a large corpus of text that can be from the Internet.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The pretraining consists of predicting the next token (a token being usually a word, subword, or punctuation).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Throughout this pretraining, GPT models accumulate knowledge about the world and can then generate human-like text by repeatedly predicting the next token.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Typically, a subsequent training phase makes the model more truthful, useful, and harmless, usually with a technique called reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current GPT models are prone to generating falsehoods called "hallucinations".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These can be reduced with RLHF and quality data, but the problem has been getting worse for reasoning systems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Such systems are used in chatbots, which allow people to ask a question or request a task in simple text.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current models and services include ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Copilot, and Meta AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Multimodal GPT models can process different types of data (modalities) such as images, videos, sound, and text.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specialized programming languages such as Prolog were used in early AI research, but general-purpose programming languages like Python have become predominant.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The transistor density in integrated circuits has been observed to roughly double every 18 months—a trend known as Moore's law, named after the Intel co-founder Gordon Moore, who first identified it.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Improvements in GPUs have been even faster, a trend sometimes called Huang's law, named after Nvidia co-founder and CEO Jensen Huang.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The deployment of AI may be overseen by a chief automation officer (CAO).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AlphaFold 2 (2021) demonstrated the ability to approximate, in hours rather than months, the 3D structure of a protein.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2023, it was reported that AI-guided drug discovery helped find a class of antibiotics capable of killing two different types of drug-resistant bacteria.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to accelerate the search for Parkinson's disease drug treatments.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Their aim was to identify compounds that block the clumping, or aggregation, of alpha-synuclein (the protein that characterises Parkinson's disease).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] They were able to speed up the initial screening process ten-fold and reduce the cost by a thousand-fold.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is increasingly being used in medical diagnostics, including the detection of diseases such as lung cancer from medical imaging like CT scans.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] A 2026 *Nature* article titled "Dozens of AI disease-prediction models were trained on dubious data" highlighted the use of unreliable data being used to train AI medical prediction models for stroke and diabetes in 125 research articles.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Evidence suggested some of the AI tools that were developed on unreliable data had been used on patients, although it was not clear if there were adverse outcomes.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game playing programs have been used since the 1950s to demonstrate and test AI's most advanced techniques.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep Blue became the first computer chess-playing system to beat a reigning world chess champion, Garry Kasparov, on 11 May 1997.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2011, in a *Jeopardy!* quiz show exhibition match, IBM's question answering system, Watson, defeated the two greatest *Jeopardy!* champions, Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, by a significant margin.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In March 2016, AlphaGo won 4 out of 5 games of Go in a match with Go champion Lee Sedol, becoming the first computer Go-playing system to beat a professional Go player without handicaps.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Then, in 2017, it defeated Ke Jie, who was the best Go player in the world.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other programs handle imperfect-information games, such as the poker-playing program Pluribus.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] DeepMind developed increasingly generalistic reinforcement learning models, such as with MuZero, which could be trained to play chess, Go, or Atari games.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, DeepMind's AlphaStar achieved grandmaster level in StarCraft II, a particularly challenging real-time strategy game that involves incomplete knowledge of what happens on the map.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2021, an AI agent competed in a PlayStation Gran Turismo competition, winning against four of the world's best Gran Turismo drivers using deep reinforcement learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, Google DeepMind introduced SIMA, a type of AI capable of autonomously playing nine previously unseen open-world video games by observing screen output, as well as executing short, specific tasks in response to natural language instructions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In mathematics, probabilistic large language models are versatile, but can also produce wrong answers in the form of hallucinations.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The Alibaba Group developed a version of its *Qwen* models called *Qwen2-Math*, that achieved state-of-the-art performance on several mathematical benchmarks, including 84% accuracy on the MATH dataset of competition mathematics problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In January 2025, Microsoft proposed the technique *rStar-Math* that leverages Monte Carlo tree search and step-by-step reasoning, enabling a relatively small language model like *Qwen-7B* to solve 53% of the AIME 2024 and 90% of the MATH benchmark problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] When natural language is used to describe mathematical problems, converters can transform such prompts into a formal language such as Lean to define mathematical tasks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The experimental model *Gemini Deep Think* accepts natural language prompts directly and achieved gold medal results in the International Math Olympiad of 2025.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Topological deep learning integrates various topological approaches.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] According to Nicolas Firzli, director of the World Pensions & Investments Forum, it may be too early to see the emergence of highly innovative AI-informed financial products and services.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Various countries are deploying AI military applications.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The main applications enhance command and control, communications, sensors, integration and interoperability.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Research is targeting intelligence collection and analysis, logistics, cyber operations, information operations, and semiautonomous and autonomous vehicles.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies enable coordination of sensors and effectors, threat detection and identification, marking of enemy positions, target acquisition, coordination and deconfliction of distributed Joint Fires between networked combat vehicles, both human-operated and autonomous.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI has been used in military operations in Iraq, Syria, Israel and Ukraine.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) is a subfield of artificial intelligence (AI) that uses generative models to generate text, images, videos, audio, software code (vibe coding) or other forms of data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These models learn the underlying patterns and structures of their training data, and use them to generate new data in response to input, which often takes the form of natural language prompts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are software entities designed to perceive their environment, make decisions, and take actions autonomously to achieve specific goals.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] These agents can interact with users, their environment, or other agents.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are used in various applications, including virtual assistants, chatbots, autonomous vehicles, game-playing systems, and industrial robotics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents operate within the constraints of their programming, available computational resources, and hardware limitations.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] This means they are restricted to performing tasks within their defined scope and have finite memory and processing capabilities.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In real-world applications, AI agents often face time constraints for decision-making and action execution.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many AI agents incorporate learning algorithms, enabling them to improve their performance over time through experience or training.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Using machine learning, AI agents can adapt to new situations and optimise their behaviour for their designated tasks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Microsoft introduced Copilot Search in February 2023 under the name Bing Chat.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Copilot Search provides AI-generated summaries.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Google introduced an AI Mode at its Google I/O event on 20 May 2025.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] Applications of AI in this domain include AI-enabled menstruation and fertility trackers that analyze user data to offer predictions, AI-integrated sex toys (e.g., teledildonics), AI-generated sexual education content, and AI agents that simulate sexual and romantic partners (e.g., Replika).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is also used for the production of non-consensual deepfake pornography, raising significant ethical and legal concerns.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies have also been used to attempt to identify online gender-based violence and online sexual grooming of minors.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In a 2017 survey, one in five companies reported having incorporated "AI" in some offerings or processes.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the field of evacuation and disaster management, AI has been used to investigate patterns in large-scale and small-scale evacuations using historical data from GPS, videos or social media.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] During the 2024 Indian elections, US$50 million was spent on authorized AI-generated content, notably by creating deepfakes of allied (including sometimes deceased) politicians to better engage with voters, and by translating speeches to various local languages.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] The use of generative AI by law firms for legal research resulted in the creation of the global "AI Hallucination Cases" database, in April 2025, established by HEC Paris and Sciences Po legal data analysis lecturer Damien Charlotin.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p01] By 2026, judges had issued sanctions and bar associations had issued warnings due to attorney submissions to the courts containing fabricated case law citations hallucinated by AI tools.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI has potential benefits and potential risks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI may be able to advance science and find solutions for serious problems: Demis Hassabis of DeepMind hopes to "solve intelligence, and then use that to solve everything else".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, as the use of AI has become widespread, several unintended consequences and risks have been identified.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In-production systems can sometimes not factor ethics and bias into their AI training processes, especially when the AI algorithms are inherently unexplainable in deep learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning algorithms require large amounts of data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The techniques used to acquire this data have raised concerns about privacy, surveillance and copyright.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI-powered devices and services, such as virtual assistants and IoT products, continuously collect personal information, raising concerns about intrusive data gathering and unauthorized access by third parties.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The loss of privacy is further exacerbated by AI's ability to process and combine vast amounts of data, potentially leading to a surveillance society where individual activities are constantly monitored and analyzed without adequate safeguards or transparency.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Sensitive user data collected may include online activity records, geolocation data, video, or audio.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, in order to build speech recognition algorithms, Amazon has recorded millions of private conversations and allowed temporary workers to listen to and transcribe some of them.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Opinions about this widespread surveillance range from those who see it as a necessary evil to those for whom it is clearly unethical and a violation of the right to privacy.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI developers argue that this is the only way to deliver valuable applications and have developed several techniques that attempt to preserve privacy while still obtaining the data, such as data aggregation, de-identification and differential privacy.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since 2016, some privacy experts, such as Cynthia Dwork, have begun to view privacy in terms of fairness.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Generative AI is often trained on unlicensed copyrighted works, including in domains such as images or computer code; the output is then used under the rationale of "fair use".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Experts disagree about how well and under what circumstances this rationale will hold up in courts of law; relevant factors may include "the purpose and character of the use of the copyrighted work" and "the effect upon the potential market for the copyrighted work".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Website owners can indicate that they do not want their content scraped via a "robots.txt" file.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, some companies will scrape content regardless because the robots.txt file has no real authority.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, leading authors (including John Grisham and Jonathan Franzen) sued AI companies for using their work to train generative AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another discussed approach is to envision a separate *sui generis* system of protection for creations generated by AI to ensure fair attribution and compensation for human authors.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The commercial AI scene is dominated by Big Tech companies such as Alphabet Inc., Amazon, Apple Inc., Meta Platforms, and Microsoft.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some of these players already own the vast majority of existing cloud infrastructure and computing power from data centers, allowing them to entrench further in the marketplace.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Technology companies have built electricity and artificial intelligence infrastructure to facilitate the AI boom of the 2020s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2025 report from the consulting firm McKinsey & Company estimated that by 2030, $2.7 trillion would be invested into AI infrastructure and data centers in the US, surpassing World War II's Manhattan Project every month.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In January 2024, the International Energy Agency (IEA) released *Electricity 2024, Analysis and Forecast to 2026*.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is the first IEA report to make projections for data centers and power consumption by AI and cryptocurrency.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The report states that power demand for these uses might double by 2026, with the additional power consumption equaling that of Japan.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Power consumption by AI is responsible for an increase in fossil fuel use, and has delayed closings of obsolete, carbon-emitting coal energy facilities.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A ChatGPT search involves the use of 10 times the electrical energy as a Google search.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Data centers' need for more and more electrical power is such that they might max out the electrical grid.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Big Tech companies counter that AI can be used to maximize the utilization of the grid by all.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that big AI companies have begun negotiations with the US nuclear power providers to provide electricity to the data centers.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2024 Amazon purchased a Pennsylvania nuclear-powered data center for US$650 million.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In September 2024, Microsoft announced an agreement with Constellation Energy to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide Microsoft with 100% of all electric power produced by the plant for 20 years.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Reopening the plant, which suffered a partial nuclear meltdown of its Unit 2 reactor in 1979, will require Constellation to get through strict regulatory processes which will include extensive safety scrutiny from the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] If approved (this will be the first ever US re-commissioning of a nuclear plant), over 835 megawatts of power – enough for 800,000 homes – of energy will be produced.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The cost for re-opening and upgrading is estimated at US$1.6 billion and is dependent on tax breaks for nuclear power contained in the 2022 US Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] As of 2024, the US government and the state of Michigan have been investing almost US$2 billion to reopen the Palisades Nuclear reactor on Lake Michigan.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Closed since 2022, the plant was planned to be reopened in October 2025.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the last approval in September 2023, Taiwan suspended the approval of data centers north of Taoyuan with a capacity of more than 5 MW in 2024, due to power supply shortages.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Taiwan aims to phase out nuclear power by 2025.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Singapore imposed a ban on the opening of data centers in 2019 due to electric power, but in 2022, lifted this ban.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 November 2024, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) rejected an application submitted by Talen Energy for approval to supply some electricity from the nuclear power station Susquehanna to Amazon's data center.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to the Commission Chairman Willie L.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Phillips, it is a burden on the electricity grid as well as a significant cost shifting concern to households and other business sectors.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2025, a report prepared by the IEA estimated the greenhouse gas emissions from the energy consumption of AI at 180 million tons.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2035, these emissions could rise to 300–500 million tonnes depending on what measures will be taken.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is below 1.5% of the energy sector emissions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The emissions reduction potential of AI was estimated at 5% of the energy sector emissions, but rebound effects (for example if people switch from public transport to autonomous cars) can reduce it.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] YouTube, Facebook and others use recommender systems to guide users to more content.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] These AI programs were given the goal of maximizing user engagement (that is, the only goal was to keep people watching).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI learned that users tended to choose misinformation, conspiracy theories, and extreme partisan content, and, to keep them watching, the AI recommended more of it.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Users also tended to watch more content on the same subject, so the AI led people into filter bubbles where they received multiple versions of the same misinformation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This convinced many users that the misinformation was true, and ultimately undermined trust in institutions, the media and the government.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI program had correctly learned to maximize its goal, but the result was harmful to society.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the U.S. election in 2016, major technology companies took some steps to mitigate the problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 2020s, generative AI began to create images, audio, and texts that are virtually indistinguishable from real photographs, recordings, or human writing, while realistic AI-generated videos became feasible in the mid-2020s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is possible for bad actors to use this technology to create massive amounts of misinformation and computational propaganda through techniques such as deepfakes.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI pioneer and Nobel Prize-winning computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton expressed concern about AI enabling "authoritarian leaders to manipulate their electorates" on a large scale, among other risks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The ability to influence electorates has been proved in at least one study.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This same study shows more inaccurate statements from the models when they advocate for candidates of the political right.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI researchers at Microsoft, OpenAI, universities and other organisations have suggested using "personhood credentials" as a way to overcome online deception enabled by AI models.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning applications can be biased if they learn from biased data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The developers may not be aware that the bias exists.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Discriminatory behavior by some LLMs can be observed in their output.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias can be introduced by the way training data is selected and by the way a model is deployed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] If a biased algorithm is used to make decisions that can seriously harm people (as it can in medicine, finance, recruitment, housing or policing) then the algorithm may cause discrimination.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of fairness studies how to prevent harms from algorithmic biases.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 28 June 2015, Google Photos's new image labeling feature mistakenly identified Jacky Alcine and a friend as "gorillas" because they were black.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The system was trained on a dataset that contained very few images of black people, a problem called "sample size disparity".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Google "fixed" this problem by preventing the system from labelling *anything* as a "gorilla".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eight years later, in 2023, Google Photos still could not identify a gorilla, and neither could similar products from Apple, Facebook, Microsoft and Amazon.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] COMPAS is a commercial program widely used by U.S. courts to assess the likelihood of a defendant becoming a recidivist.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, Julia Angwin at ProPublica discovered that COMPAS exhibited racial bias, despite the fact that the program was not told the races of the defendants.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Although the error rate for both whites and blacks was calibrated equal at exactly 61%, the errors for each race were different—the system consistently overestimated the chance that a black person would re-offend and would underestimate the chance that a white person would not re-offend.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2017, several researchers showed that it was mathematically impossible for COMPAS to accommodate all possible measures of fairness when the base rates of re-offense were different for whites and blacks in the data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A program can make biased decisions even if the data does not explicitly mention a problematic feature (such as "race" or "gender").
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The feature will correlate with other features (like "address", "shopping history" or "first name"), and the program will make the same decisions based on these features as it would on "race" or "gender".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Criticism of COMPAS highlighted that machine learning models are designed to make "predictions" that are only valid if we assume that the future will resemble the past.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] If they are trained on data that includes the results of racist decisions in the past, machine learning models must predict that racist decisions will be made in the future.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] If an application then uses these predictions as *recommendations*, some of these "recommendations" will likely be racist.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Thus, machine learning is not well suited to help make decisions in areas where there is hope that the future will be *better* than the past.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is descriptive rather than prescriptive.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias and unfairness may go undetected because the developers are overwhelmingly white and male: among AI engineers, about 4% are black and 20% are women.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are various conflicting definitions and mathematical models of fairness.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] These notions depend on ethical assumptions, and are influenced by beliefs about society.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] One broad category is distributive fairness, which focuses on the outcomes, often identifying groups and seeking to compensate for statistical disparities.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Representational fairness tries to ensure that AI systems do not reinforce negative stereotypes or render certain groups invisible.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Procedural fairness focuses on the decision process rather than the outcome.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The most relevant notions of fairness may depend on the context, notably the type of AI application and the stakeholders.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The subjectivity in the notions of bias and fairness makes it difficult for companies to operationalize them.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having access to sensitive attributes such as race or gender is also considered by many AI ethicists to be necessary in order to compensate for biases, but it may conflict with anti-discrimination laws.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the 2022 ACM Conference on Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency a paper reported that a CLIP‑based (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training) robotic system reproduced harmful gender‑ and race‑linked stereotypes in a simulated manipulation task.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many AI systems are so complex that their designers cannot explain how they reach their decisions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Particularly with deep neural networks, in which there are many non-linear relationships between inputs and outputs.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] But some popular explainability techniques exist.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is impossible to be certain that a program is operating correctly if no one knows how exactly it works.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] There have been many cases where a machine learning program passed rigorous tests, but nevertheless learned something different than what the programmers intended.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, a system that could identify skin diseases better than medical professionals was found to actually have a strong tendency to classify images with a ruler as "cancerous", because pictures of malignancies typically include a ruler to show the scale.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another machine learning system designed to help effectively allocate medical resources was found to classify patients with asthma as being at "low risk" of dying from pneumonia.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having asthma is actually a severe risk factor, but since the patients having asthma would usually get much more medical care, they were relatively unlikely to die according to the training data.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The correlation between asthma and low risk of dying from pneumonia was real, but misleading.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] People who have been harmed by an algorithm's decision have a right to an explanation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Doctors, for example, are expected to clearly and completely explain to their colleagues the reasoning behind any decision they make.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early drafts of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation in 2016 included an explicit statement that this right exists.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Industry experts noted that this is an unsolved problem with no solution in sight.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Regulators argued that nevertheless the harm is real: if the problem has no solution, the tools should not be used.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] DARPA established the XAI ("Explainable Artificial Intelligence") program in 2014 to try to solve these problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Several approaches aim to address the transparency problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] SHAP enables to visualise the contribution of each feature to the output.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] LIME can locally approximate a model's outputs with a simpler, interpretable model.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Multitask learning provides a large number of outputs in addition to the target classification.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] These other outputs can help developers deduce what the network has learned.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deconvolution, DeepDream and other generative methods can allow developers to see what different layers of a deep network for computer vision have learned, and produce output that can suggest what the network is learning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] For generative pre-trained transformers, Anthropic developed a technique based on dictionary learning that associates patterns of neuron activations with human-understandable concepts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence provides a number of tools that are useful to bad actors, such as authoritarian governments, terrorists, criminals or rogue states.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A lethal autonomous weapon is a machine that locates, selects and engages human targets without human supervision.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Widely available AI tools can be used by bad actors to develop inexpensive autonomous weapons and, if produced at scale, they are potentially weapons of mass destruction.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Even when used in conventional warfare, they currently cannot reliably choose targets and could potentially kill an innocent person.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2014, 30 nations (including China) supported a ban on autonomous weapons under the United Nations' Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons, however the United States and others disagreed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2015, over fifty countries were reported to be researching battlefield robots.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI tools make it easier for authoritarian governments to efficiently control their citizens in several ways.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Face and voice recognition allow widespread surveillance.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning, operating this data, can classify potential enemies of the state and prevent them from hiding.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recommendation systems can precisely target propaganda and misinformation for maximum effect.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deepfakes and generative AI aid in producing misinformation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Advanced AI can make authoritarian centralized decision-making more competitive than liberal and decentralized systems such as markets.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It lowers the cost and difficulty of digital warfare and advanced spyware.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] All these technologies have been available since 2020 or earlier—AI facial recognition systems are already being used for mass surveillance in China.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are many other ways in which AI is expected to help bad actors, some of which can not be foreseen.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, machine-learning AI is able to design tens of thousands of toxic molecules in a matter of hours.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Economists have frequently highlighted the risks of redundancies from AI, and speculated about unemployment if there is no adequate social policy for full employment.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the past, technology has tended to increase rather than reduce total employment, but economists acknowledge that "we're in uncharted territory" with AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A survey of economists showed disagreement about whether the increasing use of robots and AI will cause a substantial increase in long-term unemployment, but they generally agree that it could be a net benefit if productivity gains are redistributed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Risk estimates vary; for example, in the 2010s, Michael Osborne and Carl Benedikt Frey estimated 47% of U.S. jobs are at "high risk" of potential automation, while an OECD report classified only 9% of U.S. jobs as "high risk".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The methodology of speculating about future employment levels has been criticised as lacking evidential foundation, and for implying that technology, rather than social policy, creates unemployment, as opposed to redundancies.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In April 2023, it was reported that 70% of the jobs for Chinese video game illustrators had been eliminated by generative artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early-career workers showed decreasing employment rates in some AI-exposed occupations.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Unlike previous waves of automation, many middle-class jobs may be eliminated by artificial intelligence; *The Economist* stated in 2015 that "the worry that AI could do to white-collar jobs what steam power did to blue-collar ones during the Industrial Revolution" is "worth taking seriously".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Jobs at extreme risk range from paralegals to fast food cooks, while job demand is likely to increase for care-related professions ranging from personal healthcare to the clergy.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] With the increase of loneliness in the early 21st century, AI is sometimes identified as a potential source of relief to this problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It would be possible, via human-like qualities built into AI products, for individuals to assume that this need can be met by artificial means.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In some cases, people approach artificial intelligence for companionship when they believe that they would not find acceptance due to feeling outcast.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Examples of harm coming to humans from advanced chatbots have been reported in courts in the United States, with AI companies accused of creating products that endanger humans through emotional confusion or deception.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recent public debates in artificial intelligence have increasingly focused on its broader societal and ethical implications.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It has been argued AI will become so powerful that humanity may irreversibly lose control of it.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This could, as physicist Stephen Hawking stated, "spell the end of the human race".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This scenario has been common in science fiction, when a computer or robot suddenly develops a human-like "self-awareness" (or "sentience" or "consciousness") and becomes a malevolent character.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] These sci-fi scenarios are misleading in several ways.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] First, AI does not require human-like sentience to be an existential risk.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Modern AI programs are given specific goals and use learning and intelligence to achieve them.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Philosopher Nick Bostrom argued that if one gives *almost any* goal to a sufficiently powerful AI, it may choose to destroy humanity to achieve it (he used the example of an automated paperclip factory that destroys the world to get more iron for paperclips).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Second, Yuval Noah Harari argues that AI does not require a robot body or physical control to pose an existential risk.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The essential parts of civilization are not physical.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Things like ideologies, law, government, money and the economy are built on language; they exist because there are stories that billions of people believe.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The current prevalence of misinformation suggests that an AI could use language to convince people to believe anything, even to take actions that are destructive.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Geoffrey Hinton said in 2025 that modern AI is particularly "good at persuasion" and getting better all the time.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] He asks, "Suppose you wanted to invade the capital of the US.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Do you have to go there and do it yourself?
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The opinions amongst experts and industry insiders are mixed, with sizable fractions both concerned and unconcerned by risk from eventual superintelligent AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Personalities such as Stephen Hawking, Bill Gates, and Elon Musk, as well as AI pioneers such as Geoffrey Hinton, Yoshua Bengio, Stuart Russell, Demis Hassabis, and Sam Altman, have expressed concerns about existential risk from AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2023, Geoffrey Hinton announced his resignation from Google in order to be able to "freely speak out about the risks of AI" without "considering how this impacts Google".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] He notably mentioned risks of an AI takeover, and stressed that in order to avoid the worst outcomes, establishing safety guidelines will require cooperation among those competing in use of AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, many leading AI experts endorsed the joint statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some other researchers were more optimistic.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, after 2016, the study of current and future risks and possible solutions became a serious area of research.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Friendly AI are machines that have been designed from the beginning to minimize risks and to make choices that benefit humans.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eliezer Yudkowsky, who coined the term, argues that developing friendly AI should be a higher research priority: it may require a large investment and it must be completed before AI becomes an existential risk.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machines with intelligence have the potential to use their intelligence to make ethical decisions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics provides machines with ethical principles and procedures for resolving ethical dilemmas.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics is also called computational morality, and was founded at an AAAI symposium in 2005.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Other approaches include Wendell Wallach's "artificial moral agents" and Stuart J.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Russell's three principles for developing provably beneficial machines.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Active organizations in the AI open-source community include Hugging Face, Google, EleutherAI and Meta.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Various AI models, such as Llama 2, Mistral or Stable Diffusion, have been made open-weight, meaning that their architecture and trained parameters (the "weights") are publicly available.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models can be freely fine-tuned, which allows companies to specialize them with their own data and for their own use-case.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models are useful for research and innovation but can also be misused.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since they can be fine-tuned, any built-in security measure, such as objecting to harmful requests, can be trained away until it becomes ineffective.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some researchers warn that future AI models may develop dangerous capabilities (such as the potential to drastically facilitate bioterrorism) and that once released on the Internet, they cannot be deleted everywhere if needed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] They recommend pre-release audits and cost-benefit analyses.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence projects can be guided by ethical considerations during the design, development, and implementation of an AI system.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The UK AI Safety Institute released in 2024 a testing toolset called 'Inspect' for AI safety evaluations available under an MIT open-source licence which is freely available on GitHub and can be improved with third-party packages.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It can be used to evaluate AI models in a range of areas including core knowledge, ability to reason, and autonomous capabilities.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulation of artificial intelligence is the development of public sector policies and laws for promoting and regulating AI; it is therefore related to the broader regulation of algorithms.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulatory and policy landscape for AI is an emerging issue in jurisdictions globally.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Index at Stanford, the annual number of AI-related laws passed in the 127 survey countries jumped from one passed in 2016 to 37 passed in 2022 alone.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Between 2016 and 2020, more than 30 countries adopted dedicated strategies for AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Most EU member states had released national AI strategies, as had Canada, China, India, Japan, Mauritius, the Russian Federation, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, U.S., and Vietnam.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Others were in the process of elaborating their own AI strategy, including Bangladesh, Malaysia and Tunisia.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Global Partnership on Artificial Intelligence was launched in June 2020, stating a need for AI to be developed in accordance with human rights and democratic values, to ensure public confidence and trust in the technology.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Henry Kissinger, Eric Schmidt, and Daniel Huttenlocher published a joint statement in November 2021 calling for a government commission to regulate AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, OpenAI leaders published recommendations for the governance of superintelligence, which they believe may happen in less than 10 years.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, the United Nations also launched an advisory body to provide recommendations on AI governance; the body comprises technology company executives, government officials and academics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 August 2024, the EU Artificial Intelligence Act entered into force, establishing the first comprehensive EU-wide AI regulation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe created the first international legally binding treaty on AI, called the "Framework Convention on Artificial Intelligence and Human Rights, Democracy and the Rule of Law".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It was adopted by the European Union, the United States, the United Kingdom, and other signatories.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2022 Ipsos survey, attitudes towards AI varied greatly by country; 78% of Chinese citizens, but only 35% of Americans, agreed that "products and services using AI have more benefits than drawbacks".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2023 Reuters/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans agree, and 22% disagree, that AI poses risks to humanity.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2023 Fox News poll, 35% of Americans thought it "very important", and an additional 41% thought it "somewhat important", for the federal government to regulate AI, versus 13% responding "not very important" and 8% responding "not at all important".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In November 2023, the first global AI Safety Summit was held in Bletchley Park in the UK to discuss the near and far term risks of AI and the possibility of mandatory and voluntary regulatory frameworks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] 28 countries including the United States, China, and the European Union issued a declaration at the start of the summit, calling for international co-operation to manage the challenges and risks of artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2024 at the AI Seoul Summit, 16 global AI tech companies agreed to safety commitments on the development of AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2026, the United Nations convened the inaugural meeting of the Independent International Scientific Panel on AI, a 40-member expert body established under the Global Digital Compact to produce annual evidence-based reports on AI's societal impacts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of mechanical or "formal" reasoning began with philosophers and mathematicians in antiquity.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of logic led directly to Alan Turing's theory of computation, which suggested that a machine, by shuffling symbols as simple as "0" and "1", could simulate any conceivable form of mathematical reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This, along with concurrent discoveries in cybernetics, information theory and neurobiology, led researchers to consider the possibility of building an "electronic brain".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of AI research was founded at a workshop at Dartmouth College in 1956.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The first AI program, Logic Theorist, was presented at the workshop, created by future Turing Award winner Allen Newell and future Nobel Laureate Herbert A.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many of the workshop attendees became the leaders of AI research in the 1960s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] They and their students produced programs that the press described as "astonishing": computers were learning checkers strategies, solving word problems in algebra, proving logical theorems and speaking English.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence laboratories were set up at a number of British and U.S. universities in the latter 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Researchers in the 1960s and the 1970s were convinced that their methods would eventually succeed in creating a machine with general intelligence and considered this the goal of their field.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1965 Herbert Simon predicted, "machines will be capable, within twenty years, of doing any work a man can do".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1967 Marvin Minsky agreed, writing that "within a generation ... the problem of creating 'artificial intelligence' will substantially be solved".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] They had, however, underestimated the difficulty of the problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1974, both the U.S. and British governments cut off exploratory research in response to the criticism of Sir James Lighthill and ongoing pressure from the U.S.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Congress to fund more productive projects.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Minsky and Papert's book *Perceptrons* was understood as proving that artificial neural networks would never be useful for solving real-world tasks, thus discrediting the approach altogether.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The "AI winter", a period when obtaining funding for AI projects was difficult, followed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 1980s, AI research was revived by the commercial success of expert systems, a form of AI program that simulated the knowledge and analytical skills of human experts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 1985, the market for AI had reached over a billion dollars.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the same time, Japan's fifth generation computer project inspired the U.S. and British governments to restore funding for academic research.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, beginning with the collapse of the Lisp Machine market in 1987, AI once again fell into disrepute, and a second, longer-lasting winter began.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Up to this point, most of AI's funding had gone to projects that used high-level symbols to represent mental objects like plans, goals, beliefs, and known facts.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the 1980s, some researchers began to doubt that this approach would be able to imitate all the processes of human cognition, especially perception, robotics, learning and pattern recognition, and began to look into "sub-symbolic" approaches.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Rodney Brooks rejected "representation" in general and focussed directly on engineering machines that move and survive.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Judea Pearl, Lotfi Zadeh, and others developed methods that handled incomplete and uncertain information by making reasonable guesses rather than precise logic.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] But the most important development was the revival of "connectionism", including neural network research, by Geoffrey Hinton and others.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1990, Yann LeCun successfully showed that convolutional neural networks can recognize handwritten digits, the first of many successful applications of neural networks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI gradually restored its reputation in the late 1990s and early 21st century by exploiting formal mathematical methods and by finding specific solutions to specific problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] This "narrow" and "formal" focus allowed researchers to produce verifiable results and collaborate with other fields (such as statistics, economics and mathematics).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2000, solutions developed by AI researchers were being widely used, although in the 1990s they were rarely described as "artificial intelligence" (a tendency known as the AI effect).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, several academic researchers became concerned that AI was no longer pursuing its original goal of creating versatile, fully intelligent machines.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Beginning around 2002, they founded the subfield of artificial general intelligence (or "AGI"), which had several well-funded institutions by the 2010s.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning began to dominate industry benchmarks in 2012 and was adopted throughout the field.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] For many specific tasks, other methods were abandoned.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success was based on both hardware improvements (faster computers, graphics processing units, cloud computing) and access to large amounts of data (including curated datasets, such as ImageNet).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success led to an enormous increase in interest and funding in AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The amount of machine learning research (measured by total publications) increased by 50% in the years 2015–2019.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, issues of fairness and the misuse of technology were catapulted into center stage at machine learning conferences, publications vastly increased, funding became available, and many researchers re-focussed their careers on these issues.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The alignment problem became a serious field of academic study.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the late 2010s and early 2020s, AGI companies began to deliver programs that created enormous interest.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2015, AlphaGo, developed by DeepMind, beat the world champion Go player.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] The program taught only the game's rules and developed a strategy by itself.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] GPT-3 is a large language model that was released in 2020 by OpenAI and is capable of generating high-quality human-like text.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] ChatGPT, launched on 30 November 2022, became the fastest-growing consumer software application in history, gaining over 100 million users in two months.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] It marked what is widely regarded as AI's breakout year, bringing it into the public consciousness.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] These programs, and others, inspired an aggressive AI boom, where large companies began investing billions of dollars in AI research.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Impacts, about US$50 billion annually was invested in "AI" around 2022 in the U.S. alone and about 20% of the new U.S. computer science PhD graduates have specialized in "AI".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] About 800,000 "AI"-related U.S. job openings existed in 2022.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to PitchBook research, 22% of newly funded startups in 2024 claimed to be AI companies.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosophical debates have historically sought to determine the nature of intelligence and how to make intelligent machines.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another major focus has been whether machines can be conscious, and the associated ethical implications.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Many other topics in philosophy are relevant to AI, such as epistemology and free will.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Rapid advancements have intensified public discussions on the philosophy and ethics of AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Alan Turing investigated whether machines can show intelligent behaviour and think.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] In 1950, he proposed the Turing test, which measures the ability of a machine to simulate human conversation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Since we can only observe the behavior of the machine, it does not matter if it is "actually" thinking or literally has a "mind".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig agree with Turing that intelligence must be defined in terms of external behavior, not internal structure.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, they are critical that the test requires the machine to imitate humans.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] McCarthy defines intelligence as "the computational part of the ability to achieve goals in the world".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another AI founder, Marvin Minsky, similarly describes it as "the ability to solve hard problems".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* defines it as the study of agents that perceive their environment and take actions that maximize their chances of achieving defined goals.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The many differing definitions of AI have been critically analyzed.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] During the 2020s AI boom, the term has been used as a marketing buzzword to promote products and services which do not use AI.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The International Organization for Standardization describes an AI system as a "an engineered system that generates outputs such as content, forecasts, recommendations, or decisions for a given set of human‑defined objectives, and can operate with varying levels of automation".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI systems are designed to operate with varying levels of autonomy".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] No established unifying theory or paradigm has guided AI research for most of its history.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The unprecedented success of statistical machine learning in the 2010s eclipsed all other approaches (so much so that some sources, especially in the business world, use the term "artificial intelligence" to mean "machine learning with neural networks").
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This approach is mostly sub-symbolic, soft and narrow.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Symbolic AI (or "GOFAI") simulated the high-level conscious reasoning that people use when they solve puzzles, express legal reasoning and do mathematics.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] It was highly successful at some "intelligent" tasks such as algebra or IQ tests.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, the symbolic approach failed on many tasks that humans solve easily, such as learning, recognizing an object or commonsense reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Moravec's paradox is the discovery that high-level "intelligent" tasks were easy for AI, but low level "instinctive" tasks were extremely difficult.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosopher Hubert Dreyfus had argued since the 1960s that human expertise depends on unconscious instinct rather than conscious symbol manipulation, and on having a "feel" for the situation, rather than explicit symbolic knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Although his arguments had been ridiculed and ignored when they were first presented, eventually, AI research came to agree with him.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The issue is not resolved: sub-symbolic reasoning can make many of the same inscrutable mistakes that human intuition does, such as algorithmic bias.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The emerging field of neuro-symbolic artificial intelligence attempts to bridge the two approaches.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Neats" hope that intelligent behavior is described using simple, elegant principles (such as logic, optimization, or neural networks).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Scruffies" expect that it necessarily requires solving a large number of unrelated problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Neats defend their programs with theoretical rigor, scruffies rely mainly on incremental testing to see if they work.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue was actively discussed in the 1970s and 1980s, but eventually was seen as irrelevant.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Finding a provably correct or optimal solution is intractable for many important problems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing is a set of techniques, including genetic algorithms, fuzzy logic and neural networks, that are tolerant of imprecision, uncertainty, partial truth and approximation.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing was introduced in the late 1980s and most successful AI programs in the 21st century are examples of soft computing with neural networks.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI researchers are divided as to whether to pursue the goals of artificial general intelligence and superintelligence directly or to solve as many specific problems as possible (narrow AI) in hopes these solutions will lead indirectly to the field's long-term goals.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] General intelligence is difficult to define and difficult to measure, and modern AI has had more verifiable successes by focusing on specific problems with specific solutions.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The sub-field of artificial general intelligence studies this area exclusively.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] There is no settled consensus in philosophy of mind on whether a machine can have a mind, consciousness and mental states in the same sense that human beings do.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue considers the internal experiences of the machine, rather than its external behavior.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Mainstream AI research considers this issue irrelevant because it does not affect the goals of the field: to build machines that can solve problems using intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig add that "[t]he additional project of making a machine conscious in exactly the way humans are is not one that we are equipped to take on." However, the question has become central to the philosophy of mind.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] It is also typically the central question at issue in artificial intelligence in fiction.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] David Chalmers identified two problems in understanding the mind, which he named the "hard" and "easy" problems of consciousness.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The easy problem is understanding how the brain processes signals, makes plans and controls behavior.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The hard problem is explaining how this *feels* or why it should feel like anything at all, assuming we are right in thinking that it truly does feel like something (Dennett's consciousness illusionism says this is an illusion).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] While human information processing is easy to explain, human subjective experience is difficult to explain.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] For example, it is easy to imagine a color-blind person who has learned to identify which objects in their field of view are red, but it is not clear what would be required for the person to *know what red looks like*.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Computationalism is the position in the philosophy of mind that the human mind is an information processing system and that thinking is a form of computing.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Computationalism argues that the relationship between mind and body is similar or identical to the relationship between software and hardware and thus may be a solution to the mind–body problem.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This philosophical position was inspired by the work of AI researchers and cognitive scientists in the 1960s and was originally proposed by philosophers Jerry Fodor and Hilary Putnam.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] It is difficult or impossible to reliably evaluate whether an advanced AI is sentient (has the ability to feel), and if so, to what degree.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] But if there is a significant chance that a given machine can feel and suffer, then it may be entitled to certain rights or welfare protection measures, similarly to animals.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Sapience (a set of capacities related to high intelligence, such as discernment or self-awareness) may provide another moral basis for AI rights.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Robot rights are also sometimes proposed as a practical way to integrate autonomous agents into society.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] In 2017, the European Union considered granting "electronic personhood" to some of the most capable AI systems.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Similarly to the legal status of companies, it would have conferred rights but also responsibilities.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Critics argued in 2018 that granting rights to AI systems would downplay the importance of human rights, and that legislation should focus on user needs rather than speculative futuristic scenarios.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] They also noted that robots lacked the autonomy to take part in society on their own.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Progress in AI increased interest in the topic.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Proponents of AI welfare and rights often argue that AI sentience, if it emerges, would be particularly easy to deny.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] They warn that this may be a moral blind spot analogous to slavery or factory farming, which could lead to large-scale suffering if sentient AI is created and carelessly exploited.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] A superintelligence is a hypothetical agent that would possess intelligence far surpassing that of the brightest and most gifted human mind.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] If research into artificial general intelligence produced sufficiently intelligent software, it might be able to reprogram and improve itself.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] The improved software would be even better at improving itself, leading to what I.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Good called an "intelligence explosion" and Vernor Vinge called a "singularity".
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, technologies cannot improve exponentially indefinitely, and typically follow an S-shaped curve, slowing when they reach the physical limits of what the technology can do.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Robot designer Hans Moravec, cyberneticist Kevin Warwick and inventor Ray Kurzweil have predicted that humans and machines may merge in the future into cyborgs that are more capable and powerful than either.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This idea, called transhumanism, has roots in the writings of Aldous Huxley and Robert Ettinger.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Edward Fredkin argues that "artificial intelligence is the next step in evolution", an idea first proposed by Samuel Butler's "Darwin among the Machines" as far back as 1863, and expanded upon by George Dyson in his 1998 book *Darwin Among the Machines: The Evolution of Global Intelligence*.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Thought-capable artificial beings have appeared as storytelling devices since antiquity, and have been a persistent theme in science fiction.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] A common trope in these works began with Mary Shelley's *Frankenstein*, where a human creation becomes a threat to its masters.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Clarke's and Stanley Kubrick's *2001: A Space Odyssey* (both 1968), with HAL 9000, the murderous computer in charge of the *Discovery One* spaceship, as well as *Blade Runner* (1982), *The Terminator* (1984) and *The Matrix* (1999).
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] In contrast, the rare loyal robots such as Gort from *The Day the Earth Stood Still* (1951) and Bishop from *Aliens* (1986) are less prominent in popular culture.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Isaac Asimov introduced the Three Laws of Robotics in many stories, most notably with the "Multivac" super-intelligent computer.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Asimov's laws are often brought up during lay discussions of machine ethics; while almost all artificial intelligence researchers are familiar with Asimov's laws through popular culture, they generally consider the laws useless for many reasons, one of which is their ambiguity.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Several works use AI to force us to confront the fundamental question of what makes us human, showing us artificial beings that have the ability to feel, and thus to suffer.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] This appears in Karel Čapek's *R.U.R.*, the films *A.I.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Artificial Intelligence* and *Ex Machina*, as well as the novel *Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?*, by Philip K.
[src:classic-ai/artificial-intelligence-p03] Dick considers the idea that our understanding of human subjectivity is altered by technology created with artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In known environments with available models, planning can be done offline.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Solutions can be found and evaluated prior to execution.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In dynamically unknown environments, the strategy often needs to be revised online.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Solutions usually resort to iterative trial and error processes commonly seen in artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These include dynamic programming, reinforcement learning and combinatorial optimization.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Languages used to describe planning and scheduling are often called action languages.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The difficulty of planning is dependent on the simplifying assumptions employed.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Several classes of planning problems can be identified depending on the properties the problems have in several dimensions.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Since the initial state is known unambiguously, and all actions are deterministic, the state of the world after any sequence of actions can be accurately predicted, and the question of observability is irrelevant for classical planning.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Further, plans can be defined as sequences of actions, because it is always known in advance which actions will be needed.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] With nondeterministic actions or other events outside the control of the agent, the possible executions form a tree, and plans have to determine the appropriate actions for every node of the tree.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] When full observability is replaced by partial observability, planning corresponds to a partially observable Markov decision process (POMDP).
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] If there are more than one agent, we have multi-agent planning, which is closely related to game theory.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In AI planning, planners typically input a domain model (a description of a set of possible actions which model the domain) as well as the specific problem to be solved specified by the initial state and goal, in contrast to those in which there is no input domain specified.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Such planners are called "domain independent" to emphasize the fact that they can solve planning problems from a wide range of domains.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Typical examples of domains are block-stacking, logistics, workflow management, and robot task planning.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Hence a single domain-independent planner can be used to solve planning problems in all these various domains.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] On the other hand, a route planner is typical of a domain-specific planner.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The most commonly used languages for representing planning domains and specific planning problems, such as STRIPS and PDDL for Classical Planning, are based on state variables.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Each possible state of the world is an assignment of values to the state variables, and actions determine how the values of the state variables change when that action is taken.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Since a set of state variables induce a state space that has a size that is exponential in the set, planning, similarly to many other computational problems, suffers from the curse of dimensionality and the combinatorial explosion.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An alternative language for describing planning problems is that of hierarchical task networks, in which a set of tasks is given, and each task can be either realized by a primitive action or decomposed into a set of other tasks.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This does not necessarily involve state variables, although in more realistic applications state variables simplify the description of task networks.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action model learning (sometimes abbreviated action learning) is an area of machine learning concerned with the creation and modification of a software agent's knowledge about the *effects* and *preconditions* of the *actions* that can be executed within its *environment*.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This knowledge is usually represented in a logic-based action description language and used as input for automated planners.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Learning action models is important when goals change.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] When an agent acted for a while, it can use its accumulated knowledge about actions in the domain to make better decisions.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Thus, learning action models differs from reinforcement learning.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It enables reasoning about actions instead of expensive trials in the world.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action model learning is a form of inductive reasoning, where new knowledge is generated based on the agent's *observations*.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The usual motivation for action model learning is the fact that manual specification of action models for planners is often a difficult, time-consuming, and error-prone task (especially in complex environments).
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Temporal planning can be solved with methods similar to classical planning.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The main difference is, because of the possibility of several, temporally overlapping actions with a duration being taken concurrently, that the definition of a state has to include information about the current absolute time and how far the execution of each active action has proceeded.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Further, in planning with rational or real time, the state space may be infinite, unlike in classical planning or planning with integer time.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Temporal planning is closely related to scheduling problems when uncertainty is involved and can also be understood in terms of timed automata.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The Simple Temporal Network with Uncertainty (STNU) is a scheduling problem which involves controllable actions, uncertain events and temporal constraints.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Dynamic Controllability for such problems is a type of scheduling which requires a temporal planning strategy to activate controllable actions reactively as uncertain events are observed so that all constraints are guaranteed to be satisfied.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Probabilistic planning can be solved with iterative methods such as value iteration and policy iteration, when the state space is sufficiently small.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] With partial observability, probabilistic planning is similarly solved with iterative methods, but using a representation of the value functions defined for the space of beliefs instead of states.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In artificial intelligence, preference-based planning is a form of automated planning and scheduling which focuses on producing plans that additionally satisfy as many user-specified preferences as possible.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In many problem domains, a task can be accomplished by various sequences of actions (also known as plans).
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These plans can vary in quality: there can be many ways to solve a problem, but preferred generally are ways more, e.g., cost-effective, quick, and safe.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Preference-based planners take these preferences into account when producing a plan for a given problem.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Examples of preference-based planning software include *PPLAN* and *HTNPlan-P* (preference-based hierarchical task network (HTN) planning).
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Deterministic planning was introduced with the STRIPS planning system, which is a hierarchical planner.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action names are ordered in a sequence and this is a plan for the robot.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Hierarchical planning can be compared with an automatic generated behavior tree.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The disadvantage is, that a normal behavior tree is not so expressive like a computer program.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] That means, the notation of a behavior graph contains action commands, but no loops or if-then-statements.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Conditional planning overcomes the bottleneck and introduces an elaborated notation which is similar to a control flow, known from other programming languages like Pascal.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It is very similar to program synthesis, which means a planner generates sourcecode which can be executed by an interpreter.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An early example of a conditional planner is “Warplan-C” which was introduced in the mid 1970s.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] What is the difference between a normal sequence and a complicated plan, which contains if-then-statements?
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It has to do with uncertainty at runtime of a plan.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The idea is that a plan can react to sensor signals which are unknown for the planner.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The planner generates two choices in advance.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For example, if an object was detected, then action A is executed, if an object is missing, then action B is executed.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A major advantage of conditional planning is the ability to handle partial plans.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An agent is not forced to plan everything from start to finish but can divide the problem into chunks.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This helps to reduce the state space and solves much more complex problems.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] We speak of "contingent planning" when the environment is observable through sensors, which can be faulty.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It is thus a situation where the planning agent acts under incomplete information.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For a contingent planning problem, a plan is no longer a sequence of actions but a decision tree because each step of the plan is represented by a set of states rather than a single perfectly observable state, as in the case of classical planning.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The selected actions depend on the state of the system.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For example, if it rains, the agent chooses to take the umbrella, and if it doesn't, they may choose not to take it.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Littman showed in 1998 that with branching actions, the planning problem becomes EXPTIME-complete.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A particular case of contiguous planning is represented by FOND problems - for "fully-observable and non-deterministic".
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] If the goal is specified in LTLf (linear time logic on finite trace) then the problem is always EXPTIME-complete and 2EXPTIME-complete if the goal is specified with LDLf.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Conformant planning is when the agent is uncertain about the state of the system, and it cannot make any observations.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The agent then has beliefs about the real world, but cannot verify them with sensing actions, for instance.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These problems are solved by techniques similar to those of classical planning, but where the state space is exponential in the size of the problem, because of the uncertainty about the current state.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A solution for a conformant planning problem is a sequence of actions.
[src:classic-ai/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Haslum and Jonsson have demonstrated that the problem of conformant planning is EXPSPACE-complete, and 2EXPTIME-complete when the initial situation is uncertain, and there is non-determinism in the actions outcomes.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:classic-ai/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In artificial intelligence (AI), an **expert system** is a computer system emulating the decision-making ability of a human expert.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems are designed to solve complex problems by reasoning through bodies of knowledge, represented mainly as if–then rules rather than through conventional procedural programming code.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems were among the first truly successful forms of AI software.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] They were created in the 1970s and then proliferated in the 1980s, being then widely regarded as the future of AI — before the advent of successful artificial neural networks.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] An expert system is divided into two subsystems: 1) a *knowledge base*, which represents facts and rules; and 2) an *inference engine*, which applies the rules to the known facts to deduce new facts, and can include explaining and debugging abilities.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Soon after the dawn of modern computers in the late 1940s and early 1950s, researchers started realizing the immense potential these machines had for modern society.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] One of the first challenges was to make such machines able to “think” like humans – in particular, making these machines able to make important decisions the way humans do.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The medical–healthcare field presented the tantalizing challenge of enabling these machines to make medical diagnostic decisions.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Thus, in the late 1950s, right after the information age had fully arrived, researchers started experimenting with the prospect of using computer technology to emulate human decision making.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] For example, biomedical researchers started creating computer-aided systems for diagnostic applications in medicine and biology.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These early diagnostic systems used patients’ symptoms and laboratory test results as inputs to generate a diagnostic outcome.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These systems were often described as the early forms of expert systems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] However, researchers realized that there were significant limits when using traditional methods such as flow charts, statistical pattern matching, or probability theory.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This previous situation gradually led to the development of expert systems, which used knowledge-based approaches.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These expert systems in medicine were the MYCIN expert system, the Internist-I expert system and later, in the middle of the 1980s, the CADUCEUS.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems were formally introduced around 1965 by the Stanford Heuristic Programming Project led by Edward Feigenbaum, who is sometimes termed the "father of expert systems"; other key early contributors were Bruce Buchanan and Randall Davis.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The Stanford researchers tried to identify domains where expertise was highly valued and complex, such as diagnosing infectious diseases (Mycin) and identifying unknown organic molecules (Dendral).
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems became some of the first truly successful forms of artificial intelligence (AI) software.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Research on expert systems was also active in Europe.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In the US, the focus tended to be on the use of production rule systems, first on systems hard coded on top of Lisp programming environments and then on expert system shells developed by vendors such as Intellicorp.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In Europe, research focused more on systems and expert systems shells developed in Prolog.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The advantage of Prolog systems was that they employed a form of rule-based programming that was based on formal logic.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] One such early expert system shell based on Prolog was APES.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] One of the first use cases of Prolog and APES was in the legal area namely, the encoding of a large portion of the British Nationality Act.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In the 1980s, expert systems proliferated.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Universities offered expert system courses and two-thirds of the Fortune 500 companies applied the technology in daily business activities.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Interest was international with the Fifth Generation Computer Systems project in Japan and increased research funding in Europe.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In 1981, the first IBM PC, with the PC DOS operating system, was introduced.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The imbalance between the low cost of the relatively powerful chips in the PC, compared to the much more expensive cost of processing power in the mainframes that dominated the corporate IT world at the time, created a new type of architecture for corporate computing, termed the client–server model.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Calculations and reasoning could be performed at a fraction of the price of a mainframe using a PC.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This model also enabled business units to bypass corporate IT departments and directly build their own applications.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] As a result, client-server had a tremendous impact on the expert systems market.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems were already outliers in much of the business world, requiring new skills that many IT departments did not have and were not eager to develop.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] They were a natural fit for new PC-based shells that promised to put application development into the hands of end users and experts.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Until then, the main development environment for expert systems had been high end Lisp machines from Xerox, Symbolics, and Texas Instruments.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] With the rise of the PC and client-server computing, vendors such as Intellicorp and Inference Corporation shifted their priorities to developing PC-based tools.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Also, new vendors, often financed by venture capital started appearing regularly.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The first expert system to be used in a design capacity for a large-scale product was the Synthesis of Integral Design (SID) software program, developed in 1982.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Written in Lisp, SID generated 93% of the VAX 9000 CPU logic gates.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Input to the software was a set of rules created by several expert logic designers.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] SID expanded the rules and generated software logic synthesis routines many times the size of the rules themselves.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Surprisingly, the combination of these rules resulted in an overall design that exceeded the capabilities of the experts themselves, and in many cases out-performed the human counterparts.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] While some rules contradicted others, top-level control parameters for speed and area provided the tie-breaker.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The program was highly controversial but used nevertheless due to project budget constraints.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It was terminated by logic designers after the VAX 9000 project completion.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] During the years before the middle of the 1970s, the expectations of what expert systems can accomplish in many fields tended to be extremely optimistic.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] At the start of these early studies, researchers were hoping to develop entirely automatic (i.e., completely computerized) expert systems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The expectations of people of what computers can do were frequently too idealistic.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This situation radically changed after Richard M.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Karp published his breakthrough paper: “Reducibility among Combinatorial Problems” in the early 1970s.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Thanks to Karp's work, together with other scholars, like Hubert L.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Dreyfus, it became clear that there are certain limits and possibilities when one designs computer algorithms.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] His findings describe what computers can do and what they cannot do.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Many of the computational problems related to this type of expert systems have certain pragmatic limits.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These findings laid down the groundwork that led to the next developments in the field.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In the 1990s and beyond, the term *expert system* and the idea of a standalone AI system mostly dropped from the IT lexicon.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] One is that "expert systems failed": the IT world moved on because expert systems did not deliver on their over hyped promise.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The other is the mirror opposite, that expert systems were simply victims of their success: as IT professionals grasped concepts such as rule engines, such tools migrated from being standalone tools for developing special purpose *expert* systems, to being one of many standard tools.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Other researchers suggest that Expert Systems caused inter-company power struggles when the IT organization lost its exclusivity in software modifications to users or Knowledge Engineers.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In the first decade of the 2000s, there was a "resurrection" for the technology, while using the term *rule-based systems*, with significant success stories and adoption.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Many of the leading major business application suite vendors (such as SAP, Siebel, and Oracle) integrated expert system abilities into their suite of products as a way to specify business logic.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Rule engines are no longer simply for defining the rules an expert would use but for any type of complex, volatile, and critical business logic; they often go hand in hand with business process automation and integration environments.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It can be argued that expert systems have moved into the area of business rules and business rules management systems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] An expert system is an example of a knowledge-based system.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems were the first commercial systems to use a knowledge-based architecture.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In general view, an expert system includes the following components: a knowledge base, an inference engine, an explanation facility, a knowledge acquisition facility, and a user interface.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The knowledge base represents facts about the world.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In early expert systems such as Mycin and Dendral, these facts were represented mainly as flat assertions about variables.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In later expert systems developed with commercial shells, the knowledge base took on more structure and used concepts from object-oriented programming.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The world was represented as classes, subclasses, and instances and assertions were replaced by values of object instances.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The rules worked by querying and asserting values of the objects.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The inference engine is an automated reasoning system that evaluates the current state of the knowledge-base, applies relevant rules, and then asserts new knowledge into the knowledge base.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The inference engine may also include abilities for explanation, so that it can explain to a user the chain of reasoning used to arrive at a particular conclusion by tracing back over the firing of rules that resulted in the assertion.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] There are mainly two modes for an inference engine: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The different approaches are dictated by whether the inference engine is being driven by the antecedent (left hand side) or the consequent (right hand side) of the rule.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In forward chaining an antecedent fires and asserts the consequent.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] A simple example of forward chaining would be to assert Man(Socrates) to the system and then trigger the inference engine.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It would match R1 and assert Mortal(Socrates) into the knowledge base.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Backward chaining is a bit less straight forward.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In backward chaining the system looks at possible conclusions and works backward to see if they might be true.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] So if the system was trying to determine if Mortal(Socrates) is true it would find R1 and query the knowledge base to see if Man(Socrates) is true.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] One of the early innovations of expert systems shells was to integrate inference engines with a user interface.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This could be especially powerful with backward chaining.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] If the system needs to know a particular fact but does not, then it can simply generate an input screen and ask the user if the information is known.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] So in this example, it could use R1 to ask the user if Socrates was a Man and then use that new information accordingly.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The use of rules to explicitly represent knowledge also enabled explanation abilities.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In English, if the user asked "Why is Socrates Mortal?" the system would reply "Because all men are mortal and Socrates is a man".
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] A significant area for research was the generation of explanations from the knowledge base in natural English rather than simply by showing the more formal but less intuitive rules.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] As expert systems evolved, many new techniques were incorporated into various types of inference engines.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The goal of knowledge-based systems is to make the critical information required for the system to work explicit rather than implicit.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In a traditional computer program, the logic is embedded in code that can typically only be reviewed by an IT specialist.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] With an expert system, the goal was to specify the rules in a format that was intuitive and easily understood, reviewed, and even edited by domain experts rather than IT experts.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The benefits of this explicit knowledge representation were rapid development and ease of maintenance.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Ease of maintenance is the most obvious benefit.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] First, by removing the need to write conventional code, many of the normal problems that can be caused by even small changes to a system could be avoided with expert systems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Essentially, the logical flow of the program (at least at the highest level) was simply a given for the system, simply invoke the inference engine.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This also was a reason for the second benefit: rapid prototyping.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] With an expert system shell it was possible to enter a few rules and have a prototype developed in days rather than the months or year typically associated with complex IT projects.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] A claim for expert system shells that was often made was that they removed the need for trained programmers and that experts could develop systems themselves.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In reality, this was seldom if ever true.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] While the rules for an expert system were more comprehensible than typical computer code, they still had a formal syntax where a misplaced comma or other character could cause havoc as with any other computer language.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Also, as expert systems moved from prototypes in the lab to deployment in the business world, issues of integration and maintenance became far more critical.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Inevitably demands to integrate with, and take advantage of, large legacy databases and systems arose.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] To accomplish this, integration required the same skills as any other type of system.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Multiple expertise: Several expert systems can be run simultaneously to solve a problem. and gain a higher level of expertise than a human expert.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Explanation: Expert systems always describe of how the problem was solved.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Fast response: The expert systems are fast and able to solve a problem in real-time.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Reduced cost: The cost of expertise for each user is significantly reduced.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The most common disadvantage cited for expert systems in the academic literature is the knowledge acquisition problem.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Obtaining the time of domain experts for any software application is always difficult, but for expert systems it was especially difficult because the experts were by definition highly valued and in constant demand by the organization.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] As a result of this problem, a great deal of research in the later years of expert systems was focused on tools for knowledge acquisition, to help automate the process of designing, debugging, and maintaining rules defined by experts.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] However, when looking at the life-cycle of expert systems in actual use, other problems – essentially the same problems as those of any other large system – seem at least as critical as knowledge acquisition: integration, access to large databases, and performance.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Performance could be especially problematic because early expert systems were built using tools (such as earlier Lisp versions) that interpreted code expressions without first compiling them.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This provided a powerful development environment, but with the drawback that it was virtually impossible to match the efficiency of the fastest compiled languages (such as C).
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] As a result, much effort in the later stages of expert system tool development was focused on integrating with legacy environments such as COBOL and large database systems, and on porting to more standard platforms.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These issues were resolved mainly by the client–server paradigm shift, as PCs were gradually accepted in the IT environment as a legitimate platform for serious business system development and as affordable minicomputer servers provided the processing power needed for AI applications.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Another major challenge of expert systems emerges when the size of the knowledge base increases.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This causes the processing complexity to increase.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] For instance, when an expert system with 100 million rules was envisioned as the ultimate expert system, it became obvious that such system would be too complex and it would face too many computational problems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] An inference engine would have to be able to process huge numbers of rules to reach a decision.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] How to verify that decision rules are consistent with each other is also a challenge when there are too many rules.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Usually such problem leads to a satisfiability (SAT) formulation.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] This is a well-known NP-complete problem Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] If we assume only binary variables, say n of them, and then the corresponding search space is of size 2 $^{n}$ .
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Thus, the search space can grow exponentially.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] There are also questions on how to prioritize the use of the rules to operate more efficiently, or how to resolve ambiguities (for instance, if there are too many else-if sub-structures within one rule) and so on.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Other problems are related to the overfitting and overgeneralization effects when using known facts and trying to generalize to other cases not described explicitly in the knowledge base.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Such problems exist with methods that employ machine learning approaches too.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Another problem related to the knowledge base is how to make updates of its knowledge quickly and effectively.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Also how to add a new piece of knowledge (i.e., where to add it among many rules) is challenging.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Modern approaches that rely on machine learning methods are easier in this regard.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Because of the above challenges, it became clear that new approaches to AI were required instead of rule-based technologies.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These new approaches are based on the use of machine learning techniques, along with the use of feedback mechanisms.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Expert systems require knowledge engineers to input the data, data acquisition is very hard.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The expert system may choose the most inappropriate method for solving a particular problem.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Problems of ethics in the use of any form of AI are very relevant at present.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It is a closed world with specific knowledge, in which there is no deep perception of concepts and their interrelationships until an expert provides them.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Hayes-Roth divides expert systems applications into 10 categories illustrated in the following table.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The example applications were not in the original Hayes-Roth table, and some of them arose well afterward.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Any application that is not footnoted is described in the Hayes-Roth book.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Also, while these categories provide an intuitive framework to describe the space of expert systems applications, they are not rigid categories, and in some cases an application may show traits of more than one category.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Hearsay was an early attempt at solving voice recognition through an expert systems approach.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] For the most part this category of expert systems was not all that successful.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Hearsay and all interpretation systems are essentially pattern recognition systems—looking for patterns in noisy data.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] In the case of Hearsay recognizing phonemes in an audio stream.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Other early examples were analyzing sonar data to detect Russian submarines.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] These kinds of systems proved much more amenable to a neural network AI solution than a rule-based approach.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] CADUCEUS and MYCIN were medical diagnosis systems.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The user describes their symptoms to the computer as they would to a doctor and the computer returns a medical diagnosis.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Dendral was a tool to study hypothesis formation in the identification of organic molecules.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The general problem it solved—designing a solution given a set of constraints—was one of the most successful areas for early expert systems applied to business domains such as salespeople configuring Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) VAX computers and mortgage loan application development.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] SMH.PAL is an expert system for the assessment of students with multiple disabilities.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] GARVAN-ES1 was a medical expert system, developed at the Garvan Institute of Medical Research, that provided automated clinical diagnostic comments on endocrine reports from a pathology laboratory.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It was one of the first medical expert systems to go into routine clinical use internationally and the first expert system to be used for diagnosis daily in Australia.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] The system was written in "C" and ran on a PDP-11 in 64K of memory.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It had 661 rules that were compiled; not interpreted.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Mistral is an expert system to monitor dam safety, developed in the 1990s by Ismes in Italy.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It gets data from an automatic monitoring system and performs a diagnosis of the state of the dam.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Its first copy was installed in 1992 on the Ridracoli Dam in Italy.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] It has been installed on several other dams in Italy and abroad (e.g., Itaipu Dam in Brazil), and on landslide sites under the name of Eydenet, and on monuments under the name of Kaleidos.
[src:classic-ai/expert-system] Mistral is a registered trade mark of CESI.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Traditional KRR focuses more on the declarative representation of knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Related knowledge representation formalisms mainly include vocabularies, thesaurus, semantic networks, axiom systems, frames, rules, logic programs, and ontologies.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Examples of automated reasoning engines include inference engines, theorem provers, model generators, and classifiers.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In a broader sense, parameterized models in machine learning — including neural network architectures such as convolutional neural networks and transformers — can also be regarded as a family of knowledge representation formalisms.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The question of which formalism is most appropriate for knowledge-based systems has long been a subject of extensive debate.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] For instance, Frank van Harmelen et al. discussed the suitability of logic as a knowledge representation formalism and reviewed arguments presented by anti-logicists.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Paul Smolensky criticized the limitations of symbolic formalisms and explored the possibilities of integrating it with connectionist approaches.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The earliest work in computerized knowledge representation was focused on general problem-solvers such as the General Problem Solver (GPS) system developed by Allen Newell and Herbert A.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Simon in 1959 and the Advice Taker proposed by John McCarthy also in 1959.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] GPS featured data structures for planning and decomposition.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] It would then decompose that goal into sub-goals and then set out to construct strategies that could accomplish each subgoal.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Advisor Taker, on the other hand, proposed the use of the predicate calculus to implement common sense reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Many of the early approaches to knowledge representation in Artificial Intelligence (AI) used graph representations and semantic networks, similar to knowledge graphs today.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In such approaches, problem solving was a form of graph traversal or path-finding, as in the A* search algorithm.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Typical applications included robot plan-formation and game-playing.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Other researchers focused on developing automated theorem-provers for first-order logic, motivated by the use of mathematical logic to formalise mathematics and to automate the proof of mathematical theorems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A major step in this direction was the development of the resolution method by John Alan Robinson.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In the meanwhile, John McCarthy and Pat Hayes developed the situation calculus as a logical representation of common sense knowledge about the laws of cause and effect.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Cordell Green, in turn, showed how to do robot plan-formation by applying resolution to the situation calculus.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] He also showed how to use resolution for question-answering and automatic programming.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In contrast, researchers at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) rejected the resolution uniform proof procedure paradigm and advocated the procedural embedding of knowledge instead.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The resulting conflict between the use of logical representations and the use of procedural representations was resolved in the early 1970s with the development of logic programming and Prolog, using SLD resolution to treat Horn clauses as goal-reduction procedures.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The early development of logic programming was largely a European phenomenon.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In North America, AI researchers such as Ed Feigenbaum and Frederick Hayes-Roth advocated the representation of domain-specific knowledge rather than general-purpose reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] These efforts led to the cognitive revolution in psychology and to the phase of AI focused on knowledge representation that resulted in expert systems in the 1970s and 80s, production systems, frame languages, etc.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Rather than general problem solvers, AI changed its focus to expert systems that could match human competence on a specific task, such as medical diagnosis.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Expert systems gave us the terminology still in use today where AI systems are divided into a *knowledge base*, which includes facts and rules about a problem domain, and an *inference engine*, which applies the knowledge in the knowledge base to answer questions and solve problems in the domain.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In these early systems the facts in the knowledge base tended to be a fairly flat structure, essentially assertions about the values of variables used by the rules.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Meanwhile, Marvin Minsky developed the concept of frame in the mid-1970s.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A frame is similar to an object class: It is an abstract description of a category describing things in the world, problems, and potential solutions.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] It was not long before the frame communities and the rule-based researchers realized that there was a synergy between their approaches.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Frames were good for representing the real world, described as classes, subclasses, slots (data values) with various constraints on possible values.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Rules were good for representing and utilizing complex logic such as the process to make a medical diagnosis.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Integrated systems were developed that combined frames and rules.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] One of the most powerful and well known was the 1983 Knowledge Engineering Environment (KEE) from Intellicorp.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] KEE had a complete rule engine with forward and backward chaining.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] It also had a complete frame-based knowledge base with triggers, slots (data values), inheritance, and message passing.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Although message passing originated in the object-oriented community rather than AI it was quickly embraced by AI researchers as well in environments such as KEE and in the operating systems for Lisp machines from Symbolics, Xerox, and Texas Instruments.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The integration of frames, rules, and object-oriented programming was significantly driven by commercial ventures such as KEE and Symbolics spun off from various research projects.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] At the same time, there was another strain of research that was less commercially focused and was driven by mathematical logic and automated theorem proving.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] One of the most influential languages in this research was the KL-ONE language of the mid-'80s.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] KL-ONE was a frame language that had a rigorous semantics, formal definitions for concepts such as an Is-A relation.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] KL-ONE and languages that were influenced by it such as Loom had an automated reasoning engine that was based on formal logic rather than on IF-THEN rules.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A classifier can analyze a set of declarations and infer new assertions, for example, redefine a class to be a subclass or superclass of some other class that wasn't formally specified.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In this way the classifier can function as an inference engine, deducing new facts from an existing knowledge base.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The classifier can also provide consistency checking on a knowledge base (which in the case of KL-ONE languages is also referred to as an Ontology).
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Another area of knowledge representation research was the problem of common-sense reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] An example is the frame problem, that in an event driven logic there need to be axioms that state things maintain position from one moment to the next unless they are moved by some external force.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In order to make a true artificial intelligence agent that can converse with humans using natural language and can process basic statements and questions about the world, it is essential to represent this kind of knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In addition to McCarthy and Hayes' situation calculus, one of the most ambitious programs to tackle this problem was Doug Lenat's Cyc project.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Cyc established its own Frame language and had large numbers of analysts document various areas of common-sense reasoning in that language.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The knowledge recorded in Cyc included common-sense models of time, causality, physics, intentions, and many others.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The starting point for knowledge representation is the *knowledge representation hypothesis* first formalized by Brian C.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] One of the most active areas of knowledge representation research is the Semantic Web.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Semantic Web seeks to add a layer of semantics (meaning) on top of the current Internet.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Rather than indexing web sites and pages via keywords, the Semantic Web creates large ontologies of concepts.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Searching for a concept will be more effective than traditional text only searches.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Frame languages and automatic classification play a big part in the vision for the future Semantic Web.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The automatic classification gives developers technology to provide order on a constantly evolving network of knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Defining ontologies that are static and incapable of evolving on the fly would be very limiting for Internet-based systems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The classifier technology provides the ability to deal with the dynamic environment of the Internet.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Recent projects funded primarily by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) have integrated frame languages and classifiers with markup languages based on XML.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Resource Description Framework (RDF) provides the basic capability to define classes, subclasses, and properties of objects.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Web Ontology Language (OWL) provides additional levels of semantics and enables integration with classification engines.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Knowledge-representation is a field of artificial intelligence that focuses on designing computer representations that capture information about the world that can be used for solving complex problems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The justification for knowledge representation is that conventional procedural code is not the best formalism to use to solve complex problems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Knowledge representation makes complex software easier to define and maintain than procedural code and can be used in expert systems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] For example, talking to experts in terms of business rules rather than code lessens the semantic gap between users and developers and makes development of complex systems more practical.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Knowledge representation goes hand in hand with automated reasoning because one of the main purposes of explicitly representing knowledge is to be able to reason about that knowledge, to make inferences, assert new knowledge, etc.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Virtually all knowledge representation languages have a reasoning or inference engine as part of the system.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A key trade-off in the design of knowledge representation formalisms is that between expressivity and tractability.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] First Order Logic (FOL), with its high expressive power and ability to formalise much of mathematics, is a standard for comparing the expressibility of knowledge representation languages.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Arguably, FOL has two drawbacks as a knowledge representation formalism in its own right, namely ease of use and efficiency of implementation.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Firstly, because of its high expressive power, FOL allows many ways of expressing the same information, and this can make it hard for users to formalise or even to understand knowledge expressed in complex, mathematically-oriented ways.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Secondly, because of its complex proof procedures, it can be difficult for users to understand complex proofs and explanations, and it can be hard for implementations to be efficient.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] As a consequence, unrestricted FOL can be intimidating for many software developers.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] One of the key discoveries of AI research in the 1970s was that languages that do not have the full expressive power of FOL can still provide close to the same expressive power of FOL, but can be easier for both the average developer and for the computer to understand.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Many of the early AI knowledge representation formalisms, from databases to semantic nets to production systems, can be viewed as making various design decisions about how to balance expressive power with naturalness of expression and efficiency.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In particular, this balancing act was a driving motivation for the development of IF-THEN rules in rule-based expert systems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A similar balancing act was also a motivation for the development of logic programming (LP) and the logic programming language Prolog.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Logic programs have a rule-based syntax, which is easily confused with the IF-THEN syntax of production rules.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] But logic programs have a well-defined logical semantics, whereas production systems do not.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The earliest form of logic programming was based on the Horn clause subset of FOL.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] But later extensions of LP included the negation as failure inference rule, which turns LP into a non-monotonic logic for default reasoning.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The resulting extended semantics of LP is a variation of the standard semantics of Horn clauses and FOL, and is a form of database semantics, which includes the unique name assumption and a form of closed world assumption.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] These assumptions are much harder to state and reason with explicitly using the standard semantics of FOL.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Knowledge representation and reasoning are a key enabling technology for the Semantic Web.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Languages based on the Frame model with automatic classification provide a layer of semantics on top of the existing Internet.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Rather than searching via text strings as is typical today, it will be possible to define logical queries and find pages that map to those queries.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The automated reasoning component in these systems is an engine known as the classifier.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Classifiers focus on the subsumption relations in a knowledge base rather than rules.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A classifier can infer new classes and dynamically change the ontology as new information becomes available.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] This capability is ideal for the ever-changing and evolving information space of the Internet.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Semantic Web integrates concepts from knowledge representation and reasoning with markup languages based on XML.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Resource Description Framework (RDF) provides the basic capabilities to define knowledge-based objects on the Internet with basic features such as Is-A relations and object properties.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The Web Ontology Language (OWL) adds additional semantics and integrates with automatic classification reasoners.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Knowledge extraction is the creation of knowledge from structured (relational databases, XML) and unstructured (text, documents, images) sources.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The resulting knowledge needs to be in a machine-readable and machine-interpretable format and must represent knowledge in a manner that facilitates inferencing.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Although it is methodically similar to information extraction (IE) in natural language processing (NLP) and extract, transform, load (ETL), the main criterion is that the extraction result goes beyond the creation of structured information or the transformation into a relational schema.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] It requires either the reuse of existing formal knowledge (reusing identifiers or ontologies) or the generation of a schema based on the source data.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The RDB2RDF W3C group was standardizing a language for extraction of resource description frameworks (RDF) from relational databases.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Another popular example for knowledge extraction is the transformation of Wikipedia into structured data and also the mapping to existing knowledge (see DBpedia and Freebase).
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In the early years of knowledge-based systems the knowledge-bases were fairly small.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The knowledge-bases that were meant to actually solve real problems rather than do proof of concept demonstrations needed to focus on well defined problems.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] So for example, not just medical diagnosis as a whole topic, but medical diagnosis of certain kinds of diseases.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] As knowledge-based technology scaled up, the need for larger knowledge bases and for modular knowledge bases that could communicate and integrate with each other became apparent.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] This gave rise to the discipline of ontology engineering, designing and building large knowledge bases that could be used by multiple projects.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] One of the leading research projects in this area was the Cyc project.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Cyc was an attempt to build a huge encyclopedic knowledge base that would contain not just expert knowledge but common-sense knowledge.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] In designing an artificial intelligence agent, it was soon realized that representing common-sense knowledge, knowledge that humans simply take for granted, was essential to make an AI that could interact with humans using natural language.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The language they defined was known as CycL.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] After CycL, a number of ontology languages have been developed.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Most are declarative languages, and are either frame languages, or are based on first-order logic.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] A general-purpose ontology would have to be applicable in any domain and different areas of knowledge need to be unified.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] There is a long history of work attempting to build ontologies for a variety of task domains, e.g., an ontology for liquids, the lumped element model widely used in representing electronic circuits (e.g.), as well as ontologies for time, belief, and even programming itself.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Each of these offers a way to see some part of the world.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] The lumped element model, for instance, suggests that we think of circuits in terms of components with connections between them, with signals flowing instantaneously along the connections.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] This is a useful view, but not the only possible one.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Ontologies can of course be written down in a wide variety of languages and notations (e.g., logic, LISP, etc.); the essential information is not the form of that language but the content, i.e., the set of concepts offered as a way of thinking about the world.
[src:classic-ai/knowledge-representation-and-reasoning] Simply put, the important part is notions like connections and components, not the choice between writing them as predicates or LISP constructs.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given an image representing printed text, determine the corresponding text.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, determine the textual representation of the speech.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] is a necessary subtask of speech recognition (see below).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] to discrete characters can be a very difficult process.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Also, given that words in the same language are spoken by people with different accents, the speech recognition software must be able to recognize the wide variety of input as being identical to each other in terms of its textual equivalent.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, separate it into words.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a text, transform those units and produce a spoken representation.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Text-to-speech can be used to aid the visually impaired.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] is a text-processing technique that divides text into individual words or word fragments.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] This technique results in two key components: a word index and tokenized text.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The word index is a list that maps unique words to specific numerical identifiers, and the tokenized text replaces each word with its corresponding numerical token.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] These numerical tokens are then used in various deep learning methods.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , this is fairly trivial, since words are usually separated by spaces.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The task of removing inflectional endings only and returning the base dictionary form of a word which is also known as a lemma.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Lemmatization is another technique for reducing words to their normalized form.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] But in this case, the transformation actually uses a dictionary to map words to their actual form.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] and identify the class of the morphemes.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , the structure of words) of the language being considered.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , and thus it is often possible to ignore this task entirely and simply model all possible forms of a word (e.g., "open, opens, opened, opening") as separate words.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Indian language, however, such an approach is not possible, as each dictionary entry has thousands of possible word forms.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Many words, especially common ones, can serve as multiple parts of speech.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] ; and "out" can be any of at least five different parts of speech.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The process of reducing inflected (or sometimes derived) words to a base form (e.g., "close" will be the root for "closed", "closing", "close", "closer" etc.).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Stemming yields similar results as lemmatization, but does so on grounds of rules, not a dictionary.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, find the sentence boundaries.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] (grammatical analysis) of a given sentence.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] and typical sentences have multiple possible analyses: perhaps surprisingly, for a typical sentence there may be thousands of potential parses (most of which will seem completely nonsensical to a human).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] What is the computational meaning of individual words in context?
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] How can we learn semantic representations from data?
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a stream of text, determine which items in the text map to proper names, such as people or places, and what the type of each such name is (e.g. person, location, organization).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , and in any case, is often inaccurate or insufficient.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] For example, the first letter of a sentence is also capitalized, and named entities often span several words, only some of which are capitalized.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Furthermore, many other languages in non-Western scripts (e.g.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] ) do not have any capitalization at all, and even languages with capitalization may not consistently use it to distinguish names.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] This task is also referred to as token classification.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Sentiment analysis involves identifying and classifying the emotional tone expressed in text.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] This technique involves analyzing text to determine whether the expressed sentiment is positive, negative, or neutral.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] models designed to recognize both long-term and short-term dependencies in text sequences.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The applications of sentiment analysis are diverse, extending to tasks such as categorizing customer reviews on various online platforms.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] The goal of terminology extraction is to automatically extract relevant terms from a given corpus.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] ; we have to select the meaning which makes the most sense in context.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] ; here we have to select the entity (a famous individual, a location, a company, etc.) which is referred to in context.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, identify the relationships among named entities (e.g. who is married to whom).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a sentence or larger chunk of text, determine which words ("mentions") refer to the same objects ("entities").
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] with the nouns or names to which they refer.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] This rubric includes several related tasks.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] structure of a connected text, i.e. the nature of the discourse relationships between sentences (e.g. elaboration, explanation, contrast).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] in a chunk of text (e.g. yes–no question, content question, statement, assertion, etc.).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Then, identify semantic roles that are not explicitly realized in the current sentence, classify them into arguments that are explicitly realized elsewhere in the text and those that are not specified, and resolve the former against the local text.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given two text fragments, determine if one being true entails the other, entails the other's negation, or allows the other to be either true or false.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, separate it into segments each of which is devoted to a topic, and identify the topic of the segment.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] and the relationship between the main and subsidiary argument, or the main and counter-argument within discourse.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Produce a readable summary of a chunk of text.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Often used to provide summaries of the text of a known type, such as research papers, articles in the financial section of a newspaper.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error detection and correction involves a great bandwidth of problems on all levels of linguistic analysis (phonology/orthography, morphology, syntax, semantics, pragmatics).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error correction is impactful since it affects hundreds of millions of people who use or acquire English as a second language.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] It has thus been subject to a number of shared tasks since 2011.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , this can now (2019) be considered a largely solved problem and is being marketed in various commercial applications.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Translate a text from a natural language into formal logic.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Automatically translate text from one human language to another.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] ", i.e. requiring all of the different types of knowledge that humans possess (grammar, semantics, facts about the real world, etc.) to solve properly.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Natural language understanding involves the identification of the intended semantic from the multiple possible semantics that can be derived from a natural language expression which usually takes the form of organized notations of natural language concepts.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Introduction and creation of language metamodels and ontologies are efficient but empirical solutions.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , or subjective Yes/No vs. objective True/False is expected for the construction of a basis of semantics formalization.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Convert information from computer databases or semantic intents into readable human language.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Not an NLP task proper but an extension of natural language generation and other NLP tasks is the creation of full-fledged books.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , marketed as a novel, contains sixty million words.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] , this is grounded on factual knowledge and based on text summarization.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:classic-ai/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] In information science, an **ontology** encompasses a representation, formal naming, and definitions of the categories, properties, and relations between the concepts, data, or entities that pertain to one, many, or all domains of discourse.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] More simply, an ontology is a way of showing the properties of a subject area and how they are related, by defining a set of terms and relational expressions that represent the entities in that subject area.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] The field which studies ontologies so conceived is sometimes referred to as *applied ontology*.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Every academic discipline or field, in creating its terminology, thereby lays the groundwork for an ontology.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Each uses ontological assumptions to frame explicit theories, research and applications.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Improved ontologies may improve problem solving within that domain, interoperability of data systems, and discoverability of data.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Translating research papers within every field is a problem made easier when experts from different countries maintain a controlled vocabulary of jargon between each of their languages.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] For instance, the definition and ontology of economics is a primary concern in Marxist economics, but also in other subfields of economics.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] An example of economics relying on information science occurs in cases where a simulation or model is intended to enable economic decisions, such as determining what capital assets are at risk and by how much (see risk management).
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] What ontologies in both information science and philosophy have in common is the attempt to represent entities, including both objects and events, with all their interdependent properties and relations, according to a system of categories.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Applied ontology is considered by some as a successor to prior work in philosophy.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Artificial intelligence has retained considerable attention regarding applied ontology in subfields like natural language processing within machine translation and knowledge representation, but ontology editors are being used often in a range of fields, including biomedical informatics and industry.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Such efforts often use ontology editing tools such as Protégé.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Ontology is a branch of philosophy and intersects areas such as metaphysics, epistemology, and philosophy of language, as it considers how knowledge, language, and perception relate to the nature of reality.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Metaphysics deals with questions like "what exists?" and "what is the nature of reality?".
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] One of five traditional branches of philosophy, metaphysics is concerned with exploring existence through properties, entities and relations such as those between particulars and universals, intrinsic and extrinsic properties, or essence and existence.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Metaphysics has been an ongoing topic of discussion since recorded history.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] The compound word *ontology* combines *onto-*, from the Greek ὄν, *on* (gen. ὄντος, *ontos*), i.e.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] "being; that which is", which is the present participle of the verb εἰμί, *eimí*, i.e.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] "logical discourse", see classical compounds for this type of word formation.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] While the etymology is Greek, the oldest extant record of the word itself, the Neo-Latin form *ontologia*, appeared in 1606 in the work *Ogdoas Scholastica* by Jacob Lorhard (*Lorhardus*) and in 1613 in the *Lexicon philosophicum* by Rudolf Göckel (*Goclenius*).
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] The first occurrence in English of *ontology* as recorded by the *OED* (*Oxford English Dictionary*, online edition, 2008) came in *Archeologia Philosophica Nova* or *New Principles of Philosophy* (1663) by Gideon Harvey.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Since the mid-1970s, researchers in the field of artificial intelligence (AI) have recognized that knowledge engineering is the key to building large and powerful AI systems.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] AI researchers argued that they could create new ontologies as computational models that enable certain kinds of automated reasoning, which was only marginally successful.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] In the 1980s, the AI community began to use the term *ontology* to refer to both a theory of a modeled world and a component of knowledge-based systems.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Some researchers, drawing inspiration from philosophical ontologies, viewed computational ontology as a kind of applied philosophy.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] In 1993, the widely cited web page and paper "Toward Principles for the Design of Ontologies Used for Knowledge Sharing" by Tom Gruber used *ontology* as a technical term in computer science closely related to earlier idea of semantic networks and taxonomies.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Though not yet widely adopted in academic discourse, such models propose phased approaches to ethical harmonization and structural emergence.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Contemporary ontologies share many structural similarities, regardless of the language in which they are expressed.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Most ontologies describe individuals (instances), classes (concepts), attributes and relations.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] A domain ontology (or domain-specific ontology) represents concepts which belong to a realm of the world, such as biology or politics.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Each domain ontology typically models domain-specific definitions of terms.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] For example, the word *card* has many different meanings.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] An ontology about the domain of poker would model the "playing card" meaning of the word, while an ontology about the domain of computer hardware would model the "punched card" and "video card" meanings.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Since domain ontologies are written by different people, they represent concepts in very specific and unique ways, and are often incompatible within the same project.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] As systems that rely on domain ontologies expand, they often need to merge domain ontologies by hand-tuning each entity or using a combination of software merging and hand-tuning.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] This presents a challenge to the ontology designer.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Different ontologies in the same domain arise due to different languages, different intended usage of the ontologies, and different perceptions of the domain (based on cultural background, education, ideology, etc.).
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] At present, merging ontologies that are not developed from a common upper ontology is a largely manual process and therefore time-consuming and expensive.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Domain ontologies that use the same upper ontology to provide a set of basic elements with which to specify the meanings of the domain ontology entities can be merged with less effort.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] There are studies on generalized techniques for merging ontologies, but this area of research is still ongoing, and it is a recent event to see the issue sidestepped by having multiple domain ontologies using the same upper ontology like the OBO Foundry.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] An upper ontology (or foundation ontology) is a model of the commonly shared relations and objects that are generally applicable across a wide range of domain ontologies.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] It usually employs a core glossary that overarches the terms and associated object descriptions as they are used in various relevant domain ontologies.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] Standardized upper ontologies available for use include BFO, Dublin Core, GFO, Cyc, SUMO, UMBEL, and DOLCE.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] WordNet has been considered an upper ontology by some and has been used as a linguistic tool for learning domain ontologies.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] The Gellish ontology is an example of a combination of an upper and a domain ontology.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] A survey of ontology visualization methods is presented by Katifori et al.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] An updated survey of ontology visualization methods and tools was published by Dudás et al.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] The most established ontology visualization methods, namely indented tree and graph visualization are evaluated by Fu et al.
[src:classic-ai/ontology-information-science] A visual language for ontologies represented in OWL is specified by the *Visual Notation for OWL Ontologies (VOWL)*.
